text: values RLum.Data.Curve data.frame (required): RLum.Data.Curve data.frame measured curve data type stimulation time (t) (values[,1]) measured counts (cts) (values[,2]). delta vector (optional): stimulation rate parameter, value given, optimal value estimated automatically (see details). Smaller values delta produce points rising tail curve.

title: Transform a CW-OSL curve into a pHM-OSL curve via interpolation under hyperbolic modulation conditions — CW2pHMi
text: complete procedure transformation described Bos & Wallinga (2012). input data.frame consists two columns: time (t) count values (CW(t)) Internal transformation steps (1) log(CW-OSL) values (2) Calculate t' transformed time: $$t' = t-(1/\delta)*log(1+\delta*t)$$ (3) Interpolate CW(t'), .e. use log(CW(t)) obtain count values transformed time (t'). Values beyond min(t) max(t) produce NA values. (4) Select values t' < min(t), .e. values beyond time resolution t. Select first two values transformed data set contain NA values use values linear fit using lm. (5) Extrapolate values t' < min(t) based previously obtained fit parameters. (6) Transform values using $$pHM(t) = (\delta*t/(1+\delta*t))*c*CW(t')$$ $$c = (1+\delta*P)/\delta*P$$ $$P = length(stimulation~period)$$ (7) Combine values truncate values t' > max(t) NOTE: number values t' < min(t) depends stimulation rate parameter delta. avoid production many artificial data raising tail determined pHM curve, recommended use automatic estimation routine delta, .e. provide value delta.

title: Transform a CW-OSL curve into a pHM-OSL curve via interpolation under hyperbolic modulation conditions — CW2pHMi
text: According Bos & Wallinga (2012), number extrapolated points limited avoid artificial intensity data. delta provided manually two points extrapolated, warning message returned. function approx may produce Inf NaN data. function tries manually interpolate values calculating mean using adjacent channels. two invalid values succeeding, values removed interpolation attempted. every case warning message shown.

code: ##(1) - simple transformation  ##load CW-OSL curve data data(ExampleData.CW_OSL_Curve, envir = environment())  ##transform values values.transformed<-CW2pHMi(ExampleData.CW_OSL_Curve)  ##plot plot(values.transformed$x, values.transformed$y.t, log = "x")   ##(2) - load CW-OSL curve from BIN-file and plot transformed values  ##load BINfile #BINfileData<-readBIN2R("[path to BIN-file]") data(ExampleData.BINfileData, envir = environment())  ##grep first CW-OSL curve from ALQ 1 curve.ID<-CWOSL.SAR.Data@METADATA[CWOSL.SAR.Data@METADATA[,"LTYPE"]=="OSL" &                                     CWOSL.SAR.Data@METADATA[,"POSITION"]==1                                   ,"ID"]  curve.HIGH<-CWOSL.SAR.Data@METADATA[CWOSL.SAR.Data@METADATA[,"ID"]==curve.ID[1]                                     ,"HIGH"]  curve.NPOINTS<-CWOSL.SAR.Data@METADATA[CWOSL.SAR.Data@METADATA[,"ID"]==curve.ID[1]                                        ,"NPOINTS"]  ##combine curve to data set  curve<-data.frame(x = seq(curve.HIGH/curve.NPOINTS,curve.HIGH,                           by = curve.HIGH/curve.NPOINTS),                   y=unlist(CWOSL.SAR.Data@DATA[curve.ID[1]]))   ##transform values  curve.transformed <- CW2pHMi(curve)  ##plot curve plot(curve.transformed$x, curve.transformed$y.t, log = "x")    ##(3) - produce Fig. 4 from Bos & Wallinga (2012)  ##load data data(ExampleData.CW_OSL_Curve, envir = environment()) values <- CW_Curve.BosWallinga2012  ##open plot area plot(NA, NA,      xlim=c(0.001,10),      ylim=c(0,8000),      ylab="pseudo OSL (cts/0.01 s)",      xlab="t [s]",      log="x",      main="Fig. 4 - Bos & Wallinga (2012)")  values.t<-CW2pLMi(values, P=1/20) lines(values[1:length(values.t[,1]),1],CW2pLMi(values, P=1/20)[,2],       col="red" ,lwd=1.3) text(0.03,4500,"LM", col="red" ,cex=.8)  values.t<-CW2pHMi(values, delta=40) #> Warning: 56  values have been found and replaced the mean of the nearest values. lines(values[1:length(values.t[,1]),1],CW2pHMi(values, delta=40)[,2],       col="black", lwd=1.3) #> Warning: 56  values have been found and replaced the mean of the nearest values. text(0.005,3000,"HM", cex=.8)  values.t<-CW2pPMi(values, P=1/10) #> Warning: t' is beyond the time resolution. Only two data points have been extrapolated, the first 3 points have been set to 0! lines(values[1:length(values.t[,1]),1],CW2pPMi(values, P=1/10)[,2],       col="blue", lwd=1.3) #> Warning: t' is beyond the time resolution. Only two data points have been extrapolated, the first 3 points have been set to 0! text(0.5,6500,"PM", col="blue" ,cex=.8)

title: Transform a CW-OSL curve into a pLM-OSL curve via interpolation under linear modulation conditions — CW2pLMi
text: complete procedure transformation given Bos & Wallinga (2012). input data.frame consists two columns: time (t) count values (CW(t)) Nomenclature P = stimulation time (s) 1/P = stimulation rate (1/s) Internal transformation steps (1) log(CW-OSL) values (2) Calculate t' transformed time: $$t' = 1/2*1/P*t^2$$ (3) Interpolate CW(t'), .e. use log(CW(t)) obtain count values transformed time (t'). Values beyond min(t) max(t) produce NA values. (4) Select values t' < min(t), .e. values beyond time resolution t. Select first two values transformed data set contain NA values use values linear fit using lm. (5) Extrapolate values t' < min(t) based previously obtained fit parameters. (6) Transform values using $$pLM(t) = t/P*CW(t')$$ (7) Combine values truncate values t' > max(t) NOTE: number values t' < min(t) depends stimulation period (P) therefore stimulation rate 1/P. avoid production many artificial data raising tail determined pLM curves recommended use automatic estimation routine P, .e. provide value P.

title: Transform a CW-OSL curve into a pLM-OSL curve via interpolation under linear modulation conditions — CW2pLMi

title: Transform a CW-OSL curve into a pPM-OSL curve via interpolation under parabolic modulation conditions — CW2pPMi
text: complete procedure transformation given Bos & Wallinga (2012). input data.frame consists two columns: time (t) count values (CW(t)) Nomenclature P = stimulation time (s) 1/P = stimulation rate (1/s) Internal transformation steps (1) log(CW-OSL) values (2) Calculate t' transformed time: $$t' = (1/3)*(1/P^2)t^3$$ (3) Interpolate CW(t'), .e. use log(CW(t)) obtain count values transformed time (t'). Values beyond min(t) max(t) produce NA values. (4) Select values t' < min(t), .e. values beyond time resolution t. Select first two values transformed data set contain NA values use values linear fit using lm. (5) Extrapolate values t' < min(t) based previously obtained fit parameters. extrapolation limited two values. values beginning transformed curve set 0. (6) Transform values using $$pLM(t) = t^2/P^2*CW(t')$$ (7) Combine values truncate values t' > max(t) NOTE: number values t' < min(t) depends stimulation period P. avoid production many artificial data raising tail determined pPM curve, recommended use automatic estimation routine P, .e. provide value P.

code: ## Load example data data("ExampleData.Fading", envir = environment())  ## Get fading measurement data of the IR50 signal IR50_fading <- ExampleData.Fading$fading.data$IR50 head(IR50_fading) #>    LxTx LxTx.error timeSinceIrradiation #> 1 0.980     0.0490                381.6 #> 2 0.952     0.0476              12178.8 #> 3 0.924     0.0462              18183.6 #> 4 0.912     0.0456              30178.8 #> 5 0.898     0.0449              54172.8 #> 6 0.974     0.0487                378.0  ## Determine g-value and rho' for the IR50 signal IR50_fading.res <- analyse_FadingMeasurement(IR50_fading)  #>  #> [analyse_FadingMeasurement()] #>  #>  n.MC:	100 #>  tc:	3.78e+02 s #> --------------------------------------------------- #> T_0.5 interpolated:	NA #> T_0.5 predicted:	4e+11 #> g-value:		5.18 ± 0.84 (%/decade) #> g-value (norm. 2 days):	6.01 ± 0.86 (%/decade) #> --------------------------------------------------- #> rho':			3.92e-06 ± 5.53e-07 #> log10(rho'):		-5.41 ± 0.06 #> ---------------------------------------------------  ## Show g-value and rho' results gval <- get_RLum(IR50_fading.res) rhop <- get_RLum(IR50_fading.res, "rho_prime")  gval #>        FIT     MEAN        SD  Q_0.025   Q_0.16   Q_0.84  Q_0.975  TC #> x 5.182106 5.233444 0.8372966 3.687753 4.405572 6.094602 6.879693 378 #>   G_VALUE_2DAYS G_VALUE_2DAYS.ERROR T_0.5_INTERPOLATED T_0.5_PREDICTED #> x      6.010655           0.8563702                 NA    395648134315 #>   T_0.5_PREDICTED.LOWER T_0.5_PREDICTED.UPPER #> x           18339400088           18339400088 #>                                  UID #> x 2024-08-26-09:05.0.772521511185914 rhop #>           MEAN           SD      Q_0.025       Q_0.16       Q_0.84      Q_0.975 #> 1 3.921821e-06 5.528297e-07 3.031493e-06 3.377133e-06 4.454633e-06 4.952239e-06  ## Get LxTx values of the IR50 DE measurement IR50_De.LxTx <- ExampleData.Fading$equivalentDose.data$IR50  ## Calculate the De of the IR50 signal IR50_De <- plot_GrowthCurve(IR50_De.LxTx,                                 mode = "interpolation",                                 fit.method = "EXP") #> [plot_GrowthCurve()] Fit: EXP (interpolation) | De = 977.38 | D01 = 4022.47   ## Extract the calculated De and its error IR50_De.res <- get_RLum(IR50_De) De <- c(IR50_De.res$De, IR50_De.res$De.Error)  ## Apply fading correction (age conversion greatly simplified) IR50_Age <- De / 7.00 IR50_Age.corr <- calc_FadingCorr(IR50_Age, g_value = IR50_fading.res) #>  #>  #> [calc_FadingCorr()] #>  #>  >> Fading correction according to Huntley & Lamothe (2001) #>  #>  .. used g-value:	5.182 ± 0.837 %/decade #>  .. used tc:		1.198e-08 ka #>  .. used kappa:		0.0225 ± 0.0036 #>  ---------------------------------------------- #>  seed: 			NA #>  n.MC: 			10000 #>  observations: 		10000 #>  ---------------------------------------------- #>  Age (faded):		139.6261 ka ± 14.8132 ka #>  Age (corr.):		288.1629 ka ± 72.5733 ka #>  ----------------------------------------------

VALIDATE sample_1 fit_SurfaceExposure(synth_1, mu = mu, sigmaphi = sigmaphi)  #>  #>  [fit_SurfaceExposure()]  #>  #>  Estimated paramater(s): #>  ----------------------- #>  age (a):	9890 ± 369 #>  #>  Fixed parameters(s): #>  -------------------- #>  sigmaphi:	5e-10 #>  mu:		0.9 #>  #>  #>  [RLum.Results-class] #> 	 originator: fit_SurfaceExposure() #> 	 data: 5 #>  	 .. $summary : data.frame #> 	 .. $data : data.frame #> 	 .. $fit : nls #> 	 .. $args : list #> 	 .. $call : call #> 	 additional info elements:  0      ## ExampleData.SurfaceExposure$sample_2 sigmaphi <- 5e-10 age <- 10000 mu <- 0.9 x <- seq(0, 10, 0.1) Ddot <- 2.5   / 1000 / 365.25 / 24 / 60 / 60 # 2.5 Gy/ka in Seconds D0 <- 40 fun <- (sigmaphi * exp(-mu * x) *           exp(-(age * 365.25*24*3600) *                 (sigmaphi * exp(-mu * x) + Ddot/D0)) + Ddot/D0) /   (sigmaphi * exp(-mu * x) + Ddot/D0)  set.seed(666) synth_2 <- data.frame(depth = x,                       intensity = jitter(fun, 1, 0.1),                       error = runif(length(x), 0.01, 0.2))  ## VALIDATE sample_2 fit_SurfaceExposure(synth_2, mu = mu, sigmaphi = sigmaphi, Ddot = 2.5, D0 = D0)  #>  #>  [fit_SurfaceExposure()]  #>  #>  Estimated paramater(s): #>  ----------------------- #>  age (a):	9800 ± 675 #>  #>  Fixed parameters(s): #>  -------------------- #>  sigmaphi:	5e-10 #>  mu:		0.9 #>  #>  #>  [RLum.Results-class] #> 	 originator: fit_SurfaceExposure() #> 	 data: 5 #>  	 .. $summary : data.frame #> 	 .. $data : data.frame #> 	 .. $fit : nls #> 	 .. $args : list #> 	 .. $call : call #> 	 additional info elements:  0     ## ExampleData.SurfaceExposure$set_1 sigmaphi <- 5e-10 mu <- 0.9 x <- seq(0, 15, 0.2) age <- c(1e3, 1e4, 1e5, 1e6) set.seed(666)  synth_3 <- vector("list", length = length(age))  for (i in 1:length(age)) {   fun <- exp(-sigmaphi * age[i] * 365.25*24*3600 * exp(-mu * x))   synth_3[[i]] <- data.frame(depth = x,                              intensity = jitter(fun, 1, 0.05)) }   ## VALIDATE set_1 fit_SurfaceExposure(synth_3, age = age, sigmaphi = sigmaphi) #>  #>  [fit_SurfaceExposure()]  #>  #>  Shared estimated paramater(s): #>  ----------------------- #>  mu:		0.901 ± 0.00161 #>  #>  Fixed parameters(s): #>  -------------------- #>  age (a):	1000, 10000, 1e+05, 1e+06 #>  sigmaphi:	5e-10 #>  #> To apply the estimated parameters to a sample of unknown age run: #>  #> fit_SurfaceExposure(data = synth_3, sigmaphi = 5e-10, mu = 0.901) #>   #>  #>  [RLum.Results-class] #> 	 originator: fit_SurfaceExposure() #> 	 data: 5 #>  	 .. $summary : data.frame #> 	 .. $data : data.frame #> 	 .. $fit : nls #> 	 .. $args : list #> 	 .. $call : call #> 	 additional info elements:  0     ## ExampleData.SurfaceExposure$set_2 sigmaphi <- 5e-10 mu <- 0.9 x <- seq(0, 15, 0.2) age <- c(1e2, 1e3, 1e4, 1e5, 1e6) Ddot <- 1.0 / 1000 / 365.25 / 24 / 60 / 60 # 2.0 Gy/ka in Seconds D0 <- 40 set.seed(666)  synth_4 <- vector("list", length = length(age))  for (i in 1:length(age)) {   fun <- (sigmaphi * exp(-mu * x) *             exp(-(age[i] * 365.25*24*3600) *                   (sigmaphi * exp(-mu * x) + Ddot/D0)) + Ddot/D0) /     (sigmaphi * exp(-mu * x) + Ddot/D0)    synth_4[[i]] <- data.frame(depth = x,                              intensity = jitter(fun, 1, 0.05)) }   ## title: Class
text: object get_RLum: names_RLum, length_RLum, structure_RLum (required): object class RLum.Analysis class set_RLum character (required): name RLum class created originator set_RLum character (automatic): contains name calling function (function produces object); can set manually. .uid set_RLum character (automatic): sets unique ID object using internal C++ function create_UID. .pid set_RLum character (default): option provide parent id nesting . protocol set_RLum character (optional): sets protocol type analysis object. Value may used subsequent analysis functions. records set_RLum list (required): list RLum.Analysis objects info set_RLum list (optional): list containing additional info data object set_RLum: Returns RLum.Analysis object. record.id get_RLum: numeric logical (optional): IDs specific records. type logical entire id range assumed TRUE FALSE indicates selection. recordType get_RLum: character (optional): record type (e.g., "OSL"). Can also vector, multiple matching, e.g., recordType = c("OSL", "IRSL") curveType get_RLum: character (optional): curve type (e.g. "predefined" "measured") RLum.type get_RLum: character (optional): RLum object type. Defaults "RLum.Data.Curve" "RLum.Data.Spectrum". get.index get_RLum: logical (optional): return numeric vector index element RLum.Analysis object. drop get_RLum: logical (default): coerce next possible layer (RLum.Data-objects), drop = FALSE keeps original RLum.Analysis recursive get_RLum: logical (default): TRUE (default) result get_RLum() request single object object unlisted, means object list containing exactly one object returned. Mostly makes things easier, however, method used within loop might undesired. info.object get_RLum: character (optional): name wanted info element subset get_RLum: expression (optional): logical expression indicating elements rows keep: missing values taken false. argument takes precedence arguments, meaning considered subsetting object. env get_RLum: environment (default): environment passed eval enclosure. argument relevant subsetting object used manually. fullExtent structure_RLum; logical (default): extents returned data.frame full extent, .e. info elements part return well. default value FALSE data frame might become rather big. ... arguments passed underlying methods

title: Converting equivalent dose values from seconds (s) to Gray (Gy) — Second2Gray
text: Calculation De values seconds (s) Gray (Gy) $$De [Gy] = De [s] * Dose Rate [Gy/s])$$ Provided calculation error propagation methods error calculation ('se' standard error 'DR' dose rate beta-source): (1) omit (default) $$se(De) [Gy] = se(De) [s] * DR [Gy/s]$$ case standard error dose rate beta-source treated systematic (.e. non-random), error propagation omitted. However, error must considered calculation final age. (cf. Aitken, 1985, pp. 242). approach can seen method (2) (gaussian) case (random) standard error beta-source calibration 0. particular method requested depends situation prescriptive. (2) gaussian error propagation $$se(De) [Gy] = \sqrt((DR [Gy/s] * se(De) [s])^2 + (De [s] * se(DR) [Gy/s])^2)$$ Applicable assumption errors De se uncorrelated. (3) absolute error propagation $$se(De) [Gy]= abs(DR [Gy/s] * se(De) [s]) + abs(De [s] * se(DR) [Gy/s])$$ Applicable assumption errors De se correlated.

text: function performs IRSAR analysis described K-feldspar samples Erfurt et al. (2003) assuming negligible sensitivity change RF signal. General Sequence Structure (according Erfurt et al., 2003) Measuring IR-RF intensity natural dose seconds (\(RF_{nat}\)) Bleach samples solar conditions least 30 min without changing geometry Waiting least one hour Regeneration IR-RF signal least natural level (measuring (\(RF_{reg}\)) Fitting data stretched exponential function Calculate palaeodose \(D_{e}\) using parameters fitting Actually two methods supported obtain \(D_{e}\): method = "FIT" method = "SLIDE": method = "FIT" principle described follows original suggestions Erfurt et al., 2003. fitting mean count value RF_nat curve used. Function used fitting (according Erfurt et al. (2003)): $$\phi(D) = \phi_{0}-\Delta\phi(1-exp(-\lambda*D))^\beta$$ \(\phi(D)\) dose dependent IR-RF flux, \(\phi_{0}\) initial IR-RF flux, \(\Delta\phi\) dose dependent change IR-RF flux, \(\lambda\) exponential parameter, \(D\) dose \(\beta\) dispersive factor. obtain palaeodose \(D_{e}\) function changed : $$D_{e} = ln(-(\phi(D) - \phi_{0})/(-\lambda*\phi)^{1/\beta}+1)/-\lambda$$ fitting done using port algorithm nls function. method = "SLIDE" method, natural curve slid along x-axis congruence regenerated curve reached. Instead fitting allows working original data without need physical model. approach introduced RF curves Buylaert et al., 2012 Lapp et al., 2012. sliding done searching minimum squared residuals. mathematical details implementation see Frouin et al., 2017 method = "VSLIDE" "SLIDE" searching also vertically best match (.e. xy-direction.) See Kreutzer et al. (2017) Murari et al. Test parameters argument test_parameters allows pass thresholds several test parameters, evaluated function run. threshold set exceeded test parameter status set "FAILED". Intentionally parameter termed 'rejection criteria' test parameters evaluated methods parameters calculated evaluated default. These data are non pIRIR data. ### ##(1) Compile example data set based on existing example data (SAR quartz measurement) ##(a) Load example data data(ExampleData.BINfileData, envir = environment())  ##(b) Transform the values from the first position in a RLum.Analysis object object <- Risoe.BINfileData2RLum.Analysis(CWOSL.SAR.Data, pos=1)  ##(c) Grep curves and exclude the last two (one TL and one IRSL) object <- get_RLum(object, record.id = c(-29,-30))  ##(d) Define new sequence structure and set new RLum.Analysis object sequence.structure  <- c(1,2,2,3,4,4) sequence.structure <- as.vector(sapply(seq(0,length(object)-1,by = 4),                                        function(x){sequence.structure + x}))  object <-  sapply(1:length(sequence.structure), function(x){    object[[sequence.structure[x]]]  })  object <- set_RLum(class = "RLum.Analysis", records = object, protocol = "pIRIR")  ##(2) Perform pIRIR analysis (for this example with quartz OSL data!) ## title: Estimate the amount of grains on an aliquot — calc_AliquotSize
text: function can used either estimate number grains aliquot compute packing density depending arguments provided. following function used estimate number grains n: $$n = (\pi*x^2)/(\pi*y^2)*d$$ x radius aliquot size (microns), y mean radius mineral grains (mm) d packing density (value 0 1). Packing density default value packing.density 0.65, mean empirical values determined Heer et al. (2012) unpublished data Cologne luminescence laboratory. packing.density = "Inf" maximum density  \(\pi/\sqrt12 = 0.9068\ldots\) used. However, note value appropriate standard preparation procedure aliquots resembles  PECC ("Packing Equal Circles Circle") problem maximum packing density asymptotic 0.87. Monte Carlo simulation number grains aliquot can estimated Monte Carlo simulation setting MC = TRUE. parameters necessary calculate n (x, y, d) assumed normally distributed means \(\mu_x, \mu_y, \mu_d\) standard deviations \(\sigma_x, \sigma_y, \sigma_d\). mean grain size random samples taken first \(N(\mu_y, \sigma_y)\), \(\mu_y = mean.grain.size\) \(\sigma_y = (max.grain.size-min.grain.size)/4\) 95\ grains within provided grain size range. effectively takes account sieving sample still small chance grains smaller larger used mesh sizes. random sample mean grain size calculated, random subsamples drawn Monte Carlo simulation. packing density assumed normally distributed empirically determined \(\mu = 0.65\) (provided value) \(\sigma = 0.18\). normal distribution truncated d = 0.87 approximately maximum packing density can achieved PECC problem. sample diameter \(\mu = sample.diameter\) \(\sigma = 0.2\) take account variations sample disc preparation (.e. applying silicon spray disc). lower truncation point x = 0.5 used, assumes aliqouts smaller sample diameters 0.5 mm discarded. Likewise, normal distribution truncated 9.8 mm, diameter sample disc. random sample drawn normal distributions amount grains aliquot calculated. default, 10^5 iterations used, can reduced/increased MC.iter (see ...). results visualised bar- boxplot together statistical summary.

title: Calculate the cosmic dose rate — calc_CosmicDoseRate
text: function calculates total cosmic dose rate considering soft- hard-component cosmic ray flux. Internal calculation steps (1) Calculate total depth absorber hg/cm^2 (1 hg/cm^2 = 100 g/cm^2) $$absorber = depth_1*density_1 + depth_2*density_2 + ... + depth_n*density_n$$ (2) half.depth = TRUE $$absorber = absorber/2$$ (3) Calculate cosmic dose rate sea-level 55 deg. latitude ) absorber > 167 g/cm^2 (hard-component; Allkofer et al.  1975): apply equation given Prescott & Hutton (1994) (c.f. Barbouti & Rastin 1983) $$D0 = C/(((absorber+d)^\alpha+)*(absober+H))*exp(-B*absorber)$$ b) absorber < 167 g/cm^2 (soft- hard-component): derive D0 Fig. 1 Prescott & Hutton (1988). (4) Calculate geomagnetic latitude (Prescott & Stephan 1982, Prescott & Hutton 1994) $$\lambda = arcsin(0.203*cos(latitude)*cos(longitude-291)+0.979* sin(latitude))$$ (5) Apply correction geomagnetic latitude altitude sea-level. Values F, J H read Fig. 3 shown Prescott & Stephan (1982) fitted 3-degree polynomials lambda < 35 degree linear fit lambda > 35 degree. $$Dc = D0*(F+J*exp((altitude/1000)/H))$$ (6) Optional: Apply correction geomagnetic field changes last 0-80 ka (Prescott & Hutton 1994). Correction altitude factors given Table 1 Fig. 1 Prescott & Hutton (1994). Values altitude factor fitted 2-degree polynomial. altitude factor operated decimal part correction factor. $$Dc' = Dc*correctionFactor$$ Usage depth density (1) one value depth density provided, cosmic dose rate calculated exactly one sample one absorber overburden (.e. depth*density). (2) cases might useful calculate cosmic dose rate sample overlain one absorber, e.g. profile soil layers different thickness distinct difference density. can calculated providing matching number values depth density (e.g. depth = c(1, 2), density = c(1.7, 2.4)) (3) Another possibility calculate cosmic dose rate one sample profile. done providing one values depth one density. example, depth = c(1, 2, 3) density = 1.7 calculate cosmic dose rate three samples 1, 2 3 m depth sediment density 1.7 g/cm^3.

title: Calculate the cosmic dose rate — calc_CosmicDoseRate
text: Despite universal use equation calculate cosmic dose rate provided Prescott & Hutton (1994) falsely stated valid surface 10^4 hg/cm^2 standard rock. original expression Barbouti & Rastin (1983) considers muon flux (.e. hard-component) definition valid depths 10-10^4 hg/cm^2. Thus, near-surface samples (.e. depths < 167 g/cm^2) equation Prescott & Hutton (1994) underestimates total cosmic dose rate, neglects influence soft-component cosmic ray flux. samples zero depth sea-level underestimation can large ~0.1 Gy/ka. previous article, Prescott & Hutton (1988) give another approximation Barbouti & Rastin's equation form $$D = 0.21*exp(-0.070*absorber+0.0005*absorber^2)$$ valid depths 150-5000 g/cm^2. shallower depths (< 150 g/cm^2) provided graph (Fig. 1) dose rate can read. result, function employs equation Prescott & Hutton (1994) depths > 167 g/cm^2, .e. hard-component cosmic ray flux. Cosmic dose rate values depths < 167 g/cm^2 obtained "AGE" program (Gruen 2009) fitted 6-degree polynomial curve (hence reproduces graph shown Prescott & Hutton 1988). title: Fading Correction after Huntley & Lamothe (2001) — calc_FadingCorr
text: function solves equation used correcting fading affected age including error given \(g\)-value according Huntley & Lamothe (2001): $$ \frac{A_{f}}{} = 1 - \kappa * \Big[ln(\frac{}{t_c}) - 1\Big] $$ \(\kappa\) defined $$ \kappa = \frac{\frac{\mathrm{g\_value}}{ln(10)}}{100} $$ \(\) \(A_{f}\) given ka. \(t_c\) given s, however, internally recalculated ka. \(g\)-value slightly depends time irradiation prompt measurement, \(t_{c}\), always \(t_{c}\) value needs provided. \(g\)-value normalised distinct time evaluated different tc value (e.g., external irradiation), also \(t_{c}\) value \(g\)-value needs provided (argument tc.g_value \(g\)-value recalculated \(t_{c}\) measurement used estimating age applying following equation: $$\kappa_{tc} = \kappa_{tc.g} / (1 - \kappa_{tc.g} * ln(tc/tc.g))$$ $$\kappa_{tc.g} = g / 100 / ln(10)$$ error fading-corrected age determined using Monte Carlo simulation approach. Solving equation realised using uniroot. Large values n.MC significantly increase computation time. n.MC = 'auto' error estimation based stochastic process, .e. small number MC runs calculated error varies considerably every time function called, even input values. argument option n.MC = 'auto' tries find stable value standard error, .e. standard deviation values calculated MC runs (age.corr.MC), within given precision (2 digits) increasing number MC runs stepwise calculating corresponding error. determined error differ 9 values calculated previously within precision () 3 digits calculation stopped assumed error stable. Please note () duration depends input values well provided computation resources may take , (b) length (size) output vector age.corr.MC, single values produced MC runs stored, equals number MC runs (termed observations). avoid endless loop calculation stopped number observations exceeds 10^7. limitation can overwritten setting number MC runs manually, e.g. n.MC = 10000001. Note: case function checking whether calculated error stable. seed option allows recreate previously calculated results setting seed R random number generator (see set.seed details). option mixed option n.MC = 'auto'. results may appear similar, comparable! FAQ Q: \(t_{c}\) value expected? : \(t_{c}\) time seconds irradiation prompt measurement applied \(D_{e}\) measurement. However, \(t_{c}\) might differ \(t_{c}\) used estimating \(g\)-value. case SAR measurement \(t_{c}\) similar, however, differs, provide \(t_{c}\)  value (one used estimating \(g\)-value) using argument tc.g_value. Q: function find solution, ? : usually happens model parameters exceeding boundaries fading correction model (e.g., high \(g\)-value). Please check whether another fading correction model might appropriate.

code: ## Load example data (sample UNIL/NB123, see ?ExampleData.Fading) data("ExampleData.Fading", envir = environment())  ## (1) Set all relevant parameters # a. fading measurement data (IR50) fading_data <- ExampleData.Fading$fading.data$IR50  # b. Dose response curve data data <- ExampleData.Fading$equivalentDose.data$IR50  ## (2) Define required function parameters ddot <- c(7.00, 0.004) readerDdot <- c(0.134, 0.0067)  # Analyse fading measurement and get an estimate of rho'. # Note that the RLum.Results object can be directly used for further processing. # The number of MC runs is reduced for this example rhop <- analyse_FadingMeasurement(fading_data, plot = TRUE, verbose = FALSE, n.MC = 10)   ## (3) Apply the Kars et al. (2008) model to the data kars <- calc_Huntley2006(  data = data,  rhop = rhop,  ddot = ddot,  readerDdot = readerDdot,  n.MC = 25) #>     #>  #> [calc_Huntley2006()] #>  #>  ------------------------------- #>  (n/N) [-]:	 0.14 ± 0.02 #>  (n/N)_SS [-]:	 0.36 ± 0.07 #>  #>  ---------- Measured ----------- #>  DE [Gy]:	 130.97 ± 15.09 #>  D0 [Gy]:	 539.01 ± 18.77 #>  Age [ka]:	 18.71 ± 2.35 #>  #>  ---------- Un-faded ----------- #>  D0 [Gy]:	 639.61 ± 13.4 #>  #>  ---------- Simulated ---------- #>  DE [Gy]:	 253.66 ± 41.84 #>  D0 [Gy]:	 611.98 ± 4.91 #>  Age [ka]:	 36.24 ± 6.25 #>  Age @2D0 [ka]:	 174.85 ± 8.86 #>  ------------------------------- #>    if (FALSE) { # \dontrun{ # You can also provide LnTn values separately via the 'LnTn' argument. # Note, however, that the data frame for 'data' must then NOT contain # a LnTn value. See argument descriptions! LnTn <- data.frame(  LnTn = c(1.84833, 2.24833),  nTn.error = c(0.17, 0.22))  LxTx <- data[2:nrow(data), ]  kars <- calc_Huntley2006(  data = LxTx,  LnTn = LnTn,  rhop = rhop,  ddot = ddot,  readerDdot = readerDdot,  n.MC = 25) } # }

title: Apply the (un-)logged minimum age model (MAM) after Galbraith et al. (1999) to a given De distribution — calc_MinDose
text: Parameters model four parameters: par=3 (default) 3-parameter minimum age model applied, gamma=mu. par=4 4-parameter model applied instead. (Un-)logged model original version minimum dose model, basic data natural logarithms De estimates relative standard errors De estimates. value sigmab must provided ratio (e.g, 0.2 20 \ log=FALSE, modified un-logged model applied instead. essentially form original version.  gamma sigma Gy gamma becomes minimum true dose population. Note un-logged model requires sigmab absolute unit provided De values (seconds Gray). original (logged) version minimum dose model may appropriate samples (.e. De distributions), modified (un-logged) version specially designed modern-age young samples containing negative, zero near-zero De estimates (Arnold et al. 2009, p. 323). Initial values & boundaries log likelihood calculations use nlminb function box-constrained optimisation using PORT routines.  Accordingly, initial values four parameters can specified via init.values. values provided init.values reasonable starting values estimated input data.  final estimates gamma, mu, sigma p0 totally target, consider providing custom starting values via init.values. contrast previous versions function boundaries individual model parameters longer required explicitly specified. want override default boundary values use arguments gamma.lower, gamma.upper, sigma.lower, sigma.upper, p0.lower, p0.upper, mu.lower mu.upper. Bootstrap bootstrap=TRUE function applies bootstrapping method described Wallinga & Cunningham (2012). default, minimum age model produces 1000 first level 3000 second level bootstrap replicates (actually, number second level bootstrap replicates three times number first level replicates unless specified otherwise).  uncertainty sigmab 0.04 default. values can changed using arguments bs.M (first level replicates), bs.N (second level replicates) sigmab.sd (error sigmab). bs.h bandwidth kernel density estimate can specified. default, h calculated $$h = (2*\sigma_{DE})/\sqrt{n}$$ Multicore support function supports parallel computing can activated multicore=TRUE. default, number available logical CPU cores determined automatically, can changed cores. multicore support available bootstrap=TRUE spawns n R instances core get MAM estimates N M bootstrap replicates. Note option highly experimental may may work machine. Also performance gain increases larger number bootstrap replicates. Also note additional core hence R instance depending number bootstrap replicates memory usage can significantly increase. Make sure memory always available, otherwise massive performance hit. Likelihood profiles likelihood profiles generated plotted bbmle package. profile likelihood plots look different ordinary profile likelihood "[...] plot method likelihood profiles displays square root deviance difference (twice difference negative log-likelihood best fit), V-shaped cases quadratic approximation works well [...]." (Bolker 2016). details profile likelihood calculations plots please see vignettes bbmle package (also available : https://CRAN.R-project.org/package=bbmle).

\dontrun{ # (2) Re-run the model, but save results to a variable and turn # plotting of the log-likelihood profiles off. mam <- calc_MinDose(  data = ExampleData.DeValues$CA1,  sigmab = 0.1,  plot = FALSE)  # Show structure of the RLum.Results object mam  # Show summary table that contains the most relevant results res <- get_RLum(mam, "summary") res  # Plot the log likelihood profiles retroactively, because before # we set plot = FALSE plot_RLum(mam)  # Plot the dose distribution in an abanico plot and draw a line # at the minimum dose estimate plot_AbanicoPlot(data = ExampleData.DeValues$CA1,                  main = "3-parameter Minimum Age Model",                  line = mam,polygon.col = "none",                  hist = TRUE,                  rug = TRUE,                  summary = c("n", "mean", "mean.weighted", "median", "in.ci"),                  centrality = res$de,                  line.col = "red",                  grid.col = "none",                  line.label = paste0(round(res$de, 1), "\U00B1",                                      round(res$de_err, 1), " Gy"),                  bw = 0.1,                  ylim = c(-25, 18),                  summary.pos = "topleft",                  mtext = bquote("Parameters: " ~                                   sigma[b] == .(get_RLum(mam, "args")$sigmab) ~ ", " ~                                   gamma == .(round(log(res$de), 1)) ~ ", " ~                                   sigma == .(round(res$sig, 1)) ~ ", " ~                                   rho == .(round(res$p0, 2))))    # (3) Run the minimum age model with bootstrap # NOTE: Bootstrapping is computationally intensive # (3.1) run the minimum age model with default values for bootstrapping calc_MinDose(data = ExampleData.DeValues$CA1,              sigmab = 0.15,              bootstrap = TRUE)  # print summary of minimum dose and likelihood pairs summary(bs$pairs$gamma)  # Show polynomial fits of the bootstrap pairs bs$poly.fits$poly.three  # Plot various statistics of the fit using the generic plot() function par(mfcol=c(2,2)) plot(bs$poly.fits$poly.three, ask = FALSE)  # title: Calculate Lx/Tx ratio for CW-OSL curves — calc_OSLLxTxRatio
text: integrity chosen values signal background integral checked function; signal integral limits lower background integral limits. vector given input instead data.frame, artificial data.frame produced. error calculation done according Galbraith (2002). Please note: cases calculation results NaN values (example due zero-signal, therefore division 0 0), NaN values replaced 0. sigmab default value sigmab calculated assuming background constant applicable background varies , e.g., observed early light subtraction method. sig0 argument allows add extra component error final Lx/Tx error value. input treated factor multiplied already calculated LxTx result add : $$se(LxTx) = \sqrt(se(LxTx)^2 + (LxTx * sig0)^2)$$ background.count.distribution argument allows selecting distribution assumption used error calculation. According Galbraith (2002, 2014) background counts may overdispersed (.e. follow Poisson distribution, assumed photomultiplier counts). case (might normal case) accounted overdispersion estimating \(\sigma^2\) (.e. overdispersion value). Therefore relative standard error calculated : poisson $$rse(\mu_{S}) \approx \sqrt(Y_{0} + Y_{1}/k^2)/Y_{0} - Y_{1}/k$$ non-poisson $$rse(\mu_{S}) \approx \sqrt(Y_{0} + Y_{1}/k^2 + \sigma^2(1+1/k))/Y_{0} - Y_{1}/k$$ Please note using early background subtraction method combination 'non-poisson' distribution argument, corresponding Lx/Tx error may considerably increase due high sigmab value. Please check whether valid data set  necessary consider provide sigmab value using corresponding argument sigmab.

title: Calculation of the source dose rate via the date of measurement — calc_SourceDoseRate
text: Calculation source dose rate based time elapsed since last calibration irradiation source. Decay parameters assume Sr-90 beta source. $$dose.rate = D0 * exp(-log(2) / T.1/2 * t)$$  : D0 <- calibration dose rate T.1/2 <- half-life source nuclide (days) t <- time since source calibration (days) log(2) / T.1/2 equals decay constant lambda Information date measurements may taken data's original .BIN file (using e.g., BINfile <- readBIN2R() slot BINfile@METADATA$DATE) Allowed source types related values

title: Convert Nuclide Activities to Abundance and Vice Versa — convert_Activity2Concentration
text: conversion nuclide activity sample nuclide concentration performed using conversion factors based mass-related specific activity respective nuclide. Constants used function obtained https://physics.nist.gov/cuu/Constants/ atomic weights composition values https://www.nist.gov/pml/atomic-weights--isotopic-compositions-relative-atomic-masses nuclide data https://www.iaea.org/resources/databases/livechart--nuclides-advanced-version factors can calculated using equation: $$ = N_A \frac{N_{abund}}{N_{mol.mass}}  ln(2) / N.half.life $$ convert µg/g use: $$ f = / 10^6 $$ : N_A - Avogadro constant 1/mol - specific activity nuclide Bq/kg N.abund - relative natural abundance isotope N.mol.mass molar mass kg/mol N.half.life half-life nuclide s example calculating activity radionuclide U-238: N_A = 6.02214076e+23 (1/mol) T_0.5 = 1.41e+17 (s) m_U_238 = 0.23802891 (kg/mol) U_abund = 0.992745 (unitless) $$A_{U} = N_{} * U_{abund} / m_{U_238} * ln(2) / T_{1/2} = 2347046$$ (Bq/kg) $$f.U = A_{U} / 10^6$$

text: intensity spectrum re-calculated using following approach recalculate wavelength corresponding intensity values (e.g., Appendix 4 Blasse Grabmeier, 1994; Mooney Kambhampati, 2013): $$\phi_{E} = \phi_{\lambda} * \lambda^2 / (hc)$$ \(\phi_{E}\) intensity per interval energy \(E\) (1/eV), \(\phi_{\lambda}\) intensity per interval wavelength \(\lambda\) (1/nm) \(h\) (eV * s) Planck constant \(c\) (nm/s) velocity light. transforming wavelength axis (x-values) equation follow used $$E = hc/\lambda$$

title: Nonlinear Least Squares Fit for CW-OSL curves -beta version- — fit_CWCurve
text: Fitting function function CW-OSL fitting general form: $$y = I0_{1}*\lambda_{1}*exp(-\lambda_1*x) + ,\ldots, + I0_{}*\lambda_{}*exp(-\lambda_i*x) $$ \(0 < < 8\) \(\lambda\) decay constant  \(I0\) initial number trapped electrons. (used equation cf. Boetter-Jensen et al., 2003, Eq. 2.31) Start values Start values estimated automatically fitting linear function logarithmized input data set. Currently, option manually provide start parameters. Goodness fit goodness fit given pseudoR^2 value (pseudo coefficient determination). According Lave (1970), value calculated : $$pseudoR^2 = 1 - RSS/TSS$$ \(RSS = Residual~Sum~~Squares\)  \(TSS = Total~Sum~~Squares\) Error fitted component parameters 1-sigma error components calculated using function stats::confint. Due considerable calculation time, option deactivated default. addition, error components can estimated using internal R functions like summary. See nls help page information. details nonlinear regression R, see Ritz & Streibig (2008).

text: Used equation emission spectra (energy scale) can best described sum multiple Gaussian components: '$$ y = \Sigma  Ci * 1/(\sigma_{} * \sqrt(2 * \pi)) * exp(-1/2 * ((x - \mu_{})/\sigma_{}))^2) $$ parameters \(\sigma\) (peak width) \(\mu\) (peak centre) \(C\) (scaling factor). Start parameter estimation fitting algorithm spectrum deconvolution consists following steps: Peak finding Start parameter estimation Fitting via minpack.lm::nls.lm peak finding realised approach (re-)suggested Petr Pikal via R-help mailing list (https://stat.ethz.ch/pipermail/r-help/2005-November/thread.html) November 2005. goes back even earlier discussion 2001 based Prof Brian Ripley's idea. smartly uses functions stats::embed max.col identify peaks positions. use context, algorithm modified scale input data resolution (cf. source code). start parameter estimation uses random sampling range meaningful parameters repeats fitting 1000 successful fits produced set max.runs value exceeded. Currently best fit one lowest number squared residuals, parameters returned well. series curves needs analysed, recommended make trial runs, fix number components run  least 10,000 iterations (parameter method_control = list(max.runs = 10000)). title: Nonlinear Least Squares Fit for LM-OSL curves — fit_LMCurve
text: Fitting function function fitting general form: $$y = (exp(0.5)*Im_1*x/xm_1)*exp(-x^2/(2*xm_1^2)) + ,\ldots, + exp(0.5)*Im_i*x/xm_i)*exp(-x^2/(2*xm_i^2))$$ \(1 < < 8\) function equations conversion b (detrapping probability) n0 (proportional initially trapped charge) taken Kitis et al. (2008): $$xm_i=\sqrt{max(t)/b_i}$$ $$Im_i=exp(-0.5)n0/xm_i$$ Background subtraction Three methods background subtraction provided given background signal (values.bg). polynomial: default method. polynomial function fitted using glm resulting function used background subtraction: $$y = *x^4 + b*x^3 + c*x^2 + d*x + e$$ linear: linear function fitted using glm resulting function used background subtraction: $$y = *x + b$$ channel: measured background signal subtracted channel wise measured signal. Start values choice initial parameters nls-fitting crucial point fitting procedure may mainly fail due ill chosen start parameters. , three options provided: () start values (start_values) provided user, cheap guess made using detrapping values found Jain et al. (2003) quartz maximum 7 components. Based values, pseudo start parameters xm Im recalculated given data set. cases, fitting starts ultra-fast component (depending n.components) steps following values. fit achieved, error plot (plot = TRUE) pseudo curve (based pseudo start parameters) provided. may give opportunity identify appropriate start parameters visually. (b) start values provided, function works like simple nls fitting approach. (c) start parameters provided option fit.advanced = TRUE chosen, advanced start parameter estimation applied using stochastic attempt. Therefore, recalculated start parameters () used construct normal distribution. start parameters sampled randomly distribution. maximum 100 attempts made. Note: process may time consuming. Goodness fit goodness fit given pseudo-R^2 value (pseudo coefficient determination). According Lave (1970), value calculated : $$pseudoR^2 = 1 - RSS/TSS$$ \(RSS = Residual~Sum~~Squares\) \(TSS = Total~Sum~~Squares\) Error fitted component parameters 1-sigma error components calculated using function stats::confint. Due considerable calculation time, option deactivated default. addition, error components can estimated using internal R functions like summary. See nls help page information. details nonlinear regression R, see Ritz & Streibig (2008).

title: Fitting and Deconvolution of OSL Lifetime Components — fit_OSLLifeTimes
text: function intends provide easy access pulsed optically stimulated luminescence (POSL) data, order determine signal lifetimes. fitting currently optimised work -time flank POSL measurements . signal deconvolution, differential evolution optimisation combined nonlinear least-square fitting following approach Bluszcz & Adamiec (2006). Component deconvolution algorithm component deconvolution consists two steps: (1) Adaptation phase adaptation phase function tries figure optimal statistically justified number signal components following roughly approach suggested Bluszcz & Adamiec (2006). contrast work, optimisation differential evolution package 'DEoptim' used. function optimized form: $$\chi^2 = \sum(w * (n_i/c - \sum(A_i * exp(-x/(tau_i + t_p))))^2)$$ \(w = 1\) unweighted regression analysis (method_control = list(weights = FALSE)) \(w = c^2/n_i\) weighted regression analysis. default values TRUE. $$F = (\Delta\chi^2 / 2) / (\chi^2/(N - 2*m - 2))$$ (2) Final fitting method_control

text: Used equation equation used fitting $$y = (/ (1 + C * (exp(-W / (k * x))))) + c$$ W energy depth eV C dimensionless constant. c used adjust curve given signal. k Boltzmann eV/K x absolute temperature K. Error estimation error estimation done varying input parameters using given uncertainties Monte Carlo simulation. Errors assumed follow normal distribution. start_param function allows injection start parameters via argument start_param. parameters needs provided names list. names parameters optimised. Examples: start_param = list(= 1, C = 1e+5, W = 0.5, c = 0) method_control following arguments can provided via method_control. title: Merge function for RLum.Data.Curve S4 class objects — merge_RLum.Data.Curve
text: function simply allowing merge RLum.Data.Curve objects without touching objects . Merging always applied 2nd column data matrix object. Supported merge operations RLum.Data.Curve "sum" count values summed using function rowSums. "mean" mean count values calculated using function rowMeans. "median" median count values calculated using function matrixStats::rowMedians. "sd" standard deviation count values calculated using function matrixStats::rowSds. "var" variance count values calculated using function matrixStats::rowVars. "min" min values count values chosen using function matrixStats::rowMins. "max" max values count values chosen using function matrixStats::rowMins. "append" Appends count values curves one combined data curve. channel width automatically re-calculated, requires constant channel width original data. "-" row sums last objects subtracted first object. "*" row sums last objects multiplied first object. "/" Values first object divided row sums last objects.

text: data data.frame RLum.Results object (required): data.frame two columns: De (data[,1]) De error (data[,2]). plot several data sets one plot data sets must provided list, e.g. list(data.1, data.2). na.rm logical (default): exclude NA values data set prior operations. log.z logical (default): Option display z-axis logarithmic scale. Default TRUE. z.0 character numeric: User-defined central value, used centring data. One "mean", "mean.weighted" "median" numeric value (logarithm). Default "mean.weighted". dispersion character (default): measure dispersion, used drawing scatter polygon. One "qr" (quartile range), "pnn" (symmetric percentile range nn lower percentile, e.g. "p05" depicting range 5 95 %), "sd" (standard deviation) "2sd" (2 standard deviations), default "qr". Note "sd" "2sd" meaningful combination "z.0 = 'mean'" unweighted mean used centre polygon. plot.ratio numeric: Relative space, given radial versus cartesian plot part, default 0.75. rotate logical: Option turn plot 90 degrees. mtext character: additional text plot title. summary character (optional): add statistic measures centrality dispersion plot. Can one several keywords. See details available keywords. Results differ depending log-option z-scale (see details). summary.pos numeric character (default): optional position coordinates keyword (e.g. "topright") statistical summary. Alternatively, keyword "sub" may specified place summary plot header. However, latter option possible mtext used. summary.method character (default): keyword indicating method used calculate statistic summary. One "unweighted", "weighted" "MCM". See calc_Statistics details. legend character vector (optional): legend content added plot. legend.pos numeric character (default): optional position coordinates keyword (e.g. "topright") legend plotted. stats character: additional labels statistically important values plot. One following: "min", "max", "median". rug logical: Option add rug KDE part, indicate location individual values. kde logical: Option add KDE plot dispersion part, default TRUE. hist logical: Option add histogram dispersion part. meaningful one data set plotted. dots logical: Option add dot plot dispersion part. number dots exceeds space dispersion part, square indicates . boxplot logical: Option add boxplot dispersion part, default FALSE. y.axis logical: Option hide standard y-axis labels show 0 . Useful data small scatter. want suppress y-axis entirely please use yaxt == 'n' (standard graphics::par setting) instead. error.bars logical: Option show De-errors error bars De-points. Useful combination y.axis = FALSE, bar.col = "none". bar numeric (default): option add one dispersion bars (.e., bar showing 2-sigma range) centred defined values. default bar drawn according "z.0". omit bar set "bar = FALSE". bar.col character numeric (default): colour dispersion bar. Default "grey60". polygon.col character numeric (default): colour polygon showing data scatter. Sometimes polygon may omitted clarity. disable use FALSE polygon = FALSE. Default "grey80". line numeric: numeric values additional lines added. line.col character numeric: colour additional lines. line.lty integer: line type additional lines line.label character: labels additional lines. grid.col character numeric (default): colour grid lines (originating [0,0] stretching z-scale). disable grid lines use FALSE. Default "grey". frame numeric (default): option modify plot frame type. Can one 0 (frame), 1 (frame originates 0,0 runs along min/max isochrons), 2 (frame embraces 2-sigma bar), 3 (frame embraces entire plot rectangle). Default 1. bw character (default): bin-width KDE, choose numeric value manual setting. interactive logical (default): create interactive abanico plot (requires 'plotly' package) ... plot arguments pass (see graphics::plot.default). Supported : main, sub, ylab, xlab, zlab, zlim, ylim, cex, lty, lwd, pch, col, tck, tcl, , breaks. xlab must vector length two, specifying upper lower x-axes labels.

text: Abanico Plot combination classic Radial Plot (plot_RadialPlot) kernel density estimate plot (e.g plot_KDE). allows straightforward visualisation data precision, error scatter around user-defined central value combined distribution values, actual scale measured data (e.g. seconds, equivalent dose, years). principle plot shown Galbraith & Green (1990). function authors thankful thought provoking figure article. semi circle (z-axis) classic Radial Plot bent straight line , actually basis combining polar (radial) part plot Cartesian visualisation method (KDE, histogram, PDF ). Note plot allows displaying two measures distribution. One 2-sigma bar, illustrates spread value errors, polygon, stretches parts Abanico Plot (polar Cartesian) illustrates actual spread values . Since 2-sigma-bar polygon, can () filled shaded lines. change density (lines per inch, default 15) angle (default 45 degrees) shading lines, specify parameters. See ?polygon() help. Abanico Plot supports weighted mean measure centrality. obvious data (log-)normally distributed, mean (weighted ) valid measure centrality hence central dose. Accordingly, median weighted median can chosen well represent proper measure centrality (e.g. centrality = "median.weighted"). Also user-defined numeric values (e.g. central age model) can used appears appropriate. proportion polar part cartesian part Abanico Plot can modified display reasons (plot.ratio = 0.75). default, polar part spreads 75 \ shows KDE graph. statistic summary, .e. collection statistic measures centrality dispersion (measures) can added specifying one following keywords: "n" (number samples) "mean" (mean De value) "median" (median De values) "sd.rel" (relative standard deviation percent) "sd.abs" (absolute standard deviation) "se.rel" (relative standard error) "se.abs" (absolute standard error) ".2s" (percent samples 2-sigma range) "kurtosis" (kurtosis) "skewness" (skewness) Note input data statistic summary sent function calc_Statistics() depending log-option z-scale. "log.z = TRUE", summary based logarithms input data. "log.z = FALSE" linearly scaled data used. Note well, "calc_Statistics()" calculates statistic measures three different ways: unweighted, weighted MCM-based (.e., based Monte Carlo Methods). default, MCM-based version used. wish use another method, indicate appropriate keyword using argument summary.method. optional parameter layout allows modify entire plot sophisticated. element plot can addressed properties can defined. includes font type, size decoration, colours sizes plot items. infer definition specific layout style cf. get_Layout() type e.g., layout type "journal" get_Layout("journal"). layout type can modified user assigning new values list object. possible z-scale specify ticks drawn using parameter , e.g. = seq(80, 200, 20), cf. function documentation axis. Specifying tick positions manually overrides zlim-definition.

now the data set is split into sub-groups, one is manipulated data.1 <- ExampleData.DeValues[1:30,] data.2 <- ExampleData.DeValues[31:62,] * 1.3  ## now a common dataset is created from the two subgroups data.3 <- list(data.1, data.2)  ## now the two data sets are plotted in one plot plot_AbanicoPlot(data = data.3)   ## now with some graphical modification plot_AbanicoPlot(data = data.3,                  z.0 = "median",                  col = c("steelblue4", "orange4"),                  bar.col = c("steelblue3", "orange3"),                  polygon.col = c("steelblue1", "orange1"),                  pch = c(2, 6),                  angle = c(30, 50),                  summary = c("n", "in.2s", "median"))   ## create Abanico plot with predefined layout definition plot_AbanicoPlot(data = ExampleData.DeValues,                  layout = "journal")   ## now with predefined layout definition and further modifications plot_AbanicoPlot(  data = data.3,  z.0 = "median",  layout = "journal",  col = c("steelblue4", "orange4"),  bar.col = adjustcolor(c("steelblue3", "orange3"),                          alpha.f = 0.5),  polygon.col = c("steelblue3", "orange3"))   ## for further information on layout definitions see documentation ## of function get_Layout()  ## now with manually added plot content ## create empty plot with numeric output AP <- plot_AbanicoPlot(data = ExampleData.DeValues,                        pch = NA,                        output = TRUE)  ## identify data in 2 sigma range in_2sigma <- AP$data[[1]]$data.in.2s  ## restore function-internal plot parameters par(AP$par)  ## add points inside 2-sigma range points(x = AP$data[[1]]$precision[in_2sigma],        y = AP$data[[1]]$std.estimate.plot[in_2sigma],        pch = 16)  ## add points outside 2-sigma range points(x = AP$data[[1]]$precision[!in_2sigma],        y = AP$data[[1]]$std.estimate.plot[!in_2sigma],        pch = 1)

text: Fitting methods options (except LIN, QDR EXP LIN), minpack.lm::nlsLM function LM (Levenberg-Marquardt algorithm) algorithm used. Note: historical reasons Monte Carlo simulations partly function nls using port algorithm. solution found transforming function using uniroot. LIN: fits linear function data using lm: $$y = mx + n$$ QDR: fits linear function data using lm: $$y = + bx + cx^2$$ EXP: tries fit function form $$y = (1 - exp(-\frac{(x+c)}{b}))$$ Parameters b c approximated linear fit using lm. Note: b = D0 EXP LIN: works cases EXP fit fails. EXP fit fails, LIN fit done instead. EXP+LIN: tries fit exponential plus linear function form: $$y = (1-exp(-\frac{x+c}{b}) + (gx))$$ \(D_e\) calculated iteration. Note: context luminescence dating, function physical meaning. Therefore, D0 value returned. EXP+EXP: tries fit double exponential function form $$y = (a_1 (1-exp(-\frac{x}{b_1}))) + (a_2 (1 - exp(-\frac{x}{b_2})))$$ fitting procedure robust wrong start parameters improved. GOK: tries fit general-order kinetics function Guralnik et al. (2015) form $$y = (d - (1 + (\frac{1}{b}) x c)^{(-1/c)})$$ c > 0 kinetic order modifier (confused c EXP EXP+LIN!). LambertW: tries fit dose-response curve based Lambert W function according Pagonis et al. (2020). function form $$y ~ (1 + (W((R - 1) * exp(R - 1 - ((x + D_{int}) / D_{c}))) / (1 - R))) * N$$ \(W\) Lambert W function, calculated using package lamW::lambertW0, \(R\) dimensionless retrapping ratio, \(N\) total concentration trappings states cm^-3 \(D_{c} = N/R\) constant. \(D_{int}\) offset x-axis. Please finding root mode = "extrapolation" non-easy task due shape function results might unexpected. Fit weighting option fit.weights =  TRUE chosen, weights calculated using provided signal errors (Lx/Tx error): $$fit.weights = \frac{\frac{1}{error}}{\Sigma{\frac{1}{error}}}$$ Error estimation using Monte Carlo simulation Error estimation done using parametric bootstrapping approach. set Lx/Tx values constructed randomly drawing curve data sampled normal distributions. normal distribution defined input values (mean = value, sd = value.error). , dose-response curve fit attempted dataset resulting new distribution single De values. standard deviation distribution becomes error De. increasing iterations, error value becomes stable. However, naturally error decrease MC runs. Alternatively, function returns highest probability density interval estimates output, users may find useful certain circumstances. Note: may take calculation time increasing MC runs, especially composed functions (EXP+LIN EXP+EXP). error estimation done function chosen fitting method. title: Visualise natural/regenerated signal ratios — plot_NRt
code: ## load example data data("ExampleData.BINfileData", envir = environment())  ## EXAMPLE 1  ## convert Risoe.BINfileData object to RLum.Analysis object data <- Risoe.BINfileData2RLum.Analysis(object = CWOSL.SAR.Data, pos = 8, ltype = "OSL")  ## extract all OSL curves allCurves <- get_RLum(data)  ## keep only the natural and regenerated signal curves pos <- seq(1, 9, 2) curves <- allCurves[pos]  ## plot a standard NR(t) plot plot_NRt(curves)   ## re-plot with rolling mean data smoothing plot_NRt(curves, smooth = "rmean", k = 10)   ## re-plot with a logarithmic x-axis plot_NRt(curves, log = "x", smooth = "rmean", k = 5)   ## re-plot with custom axes ranges plot_NRt(curves, smooth = "rmean", k = 5,          xlim = c(0.1, 5), ylim = c(0.4, 1.6),          legend.pos = "bottomleft")   ## re-plot with smoothing spline on log scale plot_NRt(curves, smooth = "spline", log = "x",          legend.pos = "top")   ## EXAMPLE 2  # you may also use this function to check whether all # TD curves follow the same shape (making it a TnTx(t) plot). posTD <- seq(2, 14, 2) curves <- allCurves[posTD]  plot_NRt(curves, main = "TnTx(t) Plot",          smooth = "rmean", k = 20,          ylab = "TD natural / TD regenerated",          xlim = c(0, 20), legend = FALSE)   ## EXAMPLE 3  # extract data from all positions data <- lapply(1:24, FUN = function(pos) {    Risoe.BINfileData2RLum.Analysis(CWOSL.SAR.Data, pos = pos, ltype = "OSL") })  # get individual curve data from each aliquot aliquot <- lapply(data, get_RLum)  # set graphical parameters par(mfrow = c(2, 2))  # create NR(t) plots for all aliquots for (i in 1:length(aliquot)) {    plot_NRt(aliquot[[i]][pos],             main = paste0("Aliquot #", i),             smooth = "rmean", k = 20,             xlim = c(0, 10),             cex = 0.6, legend.pos = "bottomleft") }        # reset graphical parameters par(mfrow = c(1, 1))

title: Import XSYG files to R — read_XSYG2R
text: import function work? function uses 'XML' package parse file structure. sequence subsequently translated RLum.Analysis object. General structure XSYG format   far, XSYG file can contain one <Sample></Sample>, multiple sequences. record may comprise several curves. TL curve recalculation FI lexsyg device TL curves recorded time count values. Temperature values monitored heating plate stored separate curve (time vs. temperature). option recalculate.TL.curves = TRUE chosen, time values TL curve replaced temperature values. Practically, means combining two matrices (Time vs. Counts Time vs. Temperature) different row numbers time values. Three cases considered: : Heating element PMT: Photomultiplier tube Interpolation done using function approx CASE (1): nrow(matrix(PMT)) > nrow(matrix()) Missing temperature values heating element calculated using time values PMT measurement. CASE (2): nrow(matrix(PMT)) < nrow(matrix()) Missing count values PMT calculated using time values heating element measurement. CASE (3): nrow(matrix(PMT)) == nrow(matrix()) new matrix produced using temperature values heating element count values PMT. Note: Please note due recalculation temperature values based values delivered heating element, may happen multiple count values exists temperature value temperature values may also decrease heating, increase. Advanced file import allow efficient usage function, instead single path file just directory can passed input. particular case function tries extract XSYG-files found directory import . Using option internally function constructs list XSYG-files found directory. Please note recursive detection supported may lead endless loops.
code: <?xml?> <Sample>   <Sequence>     <Record>       <Curve name="first curve" />       <Curve name="curve with data">x0 , y0 ; x1 , y1 ; x2 , y2 ; x3 , y3</Curve>     </Record>   </Sequence> </Sample>

title: Calculate the gamma dose deposited within a sample taking layer-to-layer variations in radioactivity into account (according to Aitken, 1985) — scale_GammaDose
text: User Input calculate gamma dose deposited sample, user needs provide information samples influencing luminescence sample. rule thumb, sediment layers within least 30 cm radius luminescence sample taken taken account calculating gamma dose rate. However, actual range gamma radiation might different, depending emitting radioelement, water content sediment density layer (Aitken, 1985). Therefore user advised provide much detail possible physically sensible. function requires data.frame structured columns rows, samples listed rows. first column contains information layer/sample ID, second thickness (cm) layer, whilst column 3 contain NA layers sampled OSL/TL. layer OSL/TL sample taken numerical value must provided, distance (cm) measured bottom layer interest. whole layer sampled insert 0. sample taken within layer, insert numerical value >0, describes distance middle sample bottom layer cm. Columns 4 9 contain radionuclide concentrations standard errors potassium (%), thorium (ppm) uranium (ppm). Columns 10 11 give information water content uncertainty (standard error) %. layer density (g/cm3) given column 12. cell left blank. Please ensure keep column titles given example dataset (data('ExampleData.ScaleGammaDose'), see examples). user can decide dose rate conversion factors used calculate gamma dose rates. options : "Cresswelletal2018" (Cresswell et al., 2018) "Liritzisetal2013" (Liritzis et al., 2013) "Guerinetal2011" (Guerin et al., 2011) "AdamiecAitken1998" (Adamiec Aitken, 1998) Water content water content provided user calculated according : $$ ( Wet weight [g] - Dry weight [g] ) / Dry weight [g] * 100 $$ Calculations converting radionuclide concentrations dose rates, function scale dose rates based thickness layers, distances sample, water content density sediment. calculations based Aitken (1985, Appendix H). example (equivalent Aitken, 1985), assuming three layers sediment, L inert positioned infinite thick equally active layers B, dose L B due given $$ {1-f(x)}D_A $$ x distance inert medium, f(x) weighted average fractional dose x D_A denotes dose delivered . f(x) derived table H1 (Aitken, 1985), setting z = x. Consequently, dose L due B given $$ {1 - f(t-x)}D_B $$ t thickness L parameters denoted , just dose delivered B. f(t-x) derived table H1 (Aitken, 1985), setting z equal t-x. Following , dose L delivered B given $$ {2 - f(x) - f(t-x)}D_{AB} $$ Since B equally active D_{AB} = D_A = D_B. function uses value fractional dose rate layer boundary start calculation next layer. way, function able scale gamma dose rate accurately distant layers density water content constant entire section.

text: method work? function compares expected values (\(E(X)\)) variance (\(Var(X)\)) count values curve. Values threshold indicate curves comprising signal. Note: absolute difference \(E(X)\) \(Var(x)\) instead ratio chosen terms can become 0 result 0 Inf, ratio calculated.
